WEBVTT

00:04.700 --> 00:05.048
.

00:05.092 --> 00:06.919
- Previously
on "New Amsterdam"...

00:06.963 --> 00:08.312
- Isn't that why I'm here?

00:08.356 --> 00:09.096
Because you feel guilty
for ignoring your brother

00:09.139 --> 00:10.314
for all those years.

00:10.358 --> 00:12.186
- You're here
because you're my family.

00:12.229 --> 00:14.188
- That you ignored
for your whole life!

00:14.231 --> 00:17.278
- I was the one
who was ignored first!

00:17.321 --> 00:19.149
- My mother's raised
three kids,

00:19.193 --> 00:20.629
owns her own home,

00:20.672 --> 00:22.631
prays harder than anyone I know
for everyone else,

00:22.674 --> 00:25.068
and now she needs
full-time care.

00:25.112 --> 00:26.548
- What are you doing?
- I'm leaving.

00:26.591 --> 00:28.550
- No, come on.
Don't do this.

00:28.593 --> 00:30.639
- Why not?

00:30.682 --> 00:32.684
- I'm transferring you
to another therapist.

00:32.728 --> 00:33.729
I'm sorry.

00:33.772 --> 00:35.818
- I had
a tremendous breakthrough

00:35.861 --> 00:38.212
with the new patient.

00:38.255 --> 00:40.040
- Is that his hat?

00:41.650 --> 00:44.261
- ♪ Talk that talk, hey

00:44.305 --> 00:46.829
♪ Better walk that walk,
clap hands now ♪

00:46.872 --> 00:48.526
♪ Talk that talk, hey

00:48.570 --> 00:51.486
♪ Better walk that walk,
clap hands now ♪

00:51.529 --> 00:53.923
- ♪ Talk the talk, baby

00:53.966 --> 00:56.186
♪ Walk the walk

00:56.230 --> 00:58.754
♪ Talk the talk, baby

00:58.797 --> 00:59.711
♪ Walk the walk

00:59.755 --> 01:01.452
- Thank God.

01:01.496 --> 01:05.543
103 degree heat,
suffocating exhaust fumes,

01:05.587 --> 01:07.980
the sun reflecting
off every glass tower.

01:08.024 --> 01:10.548
As you can see, she took it
with great dignity.

01:10.592 --> 01:12.159
- Oh, were you burning up
out there?

01:12.202 --> 01:13.508
Come here.
I gotcha.

01:13.551 --> 01:14.900
- Goodness gracious.
- Oh, I gotcha.

01:14.944 --> 01:19.862
I think somebody needs
a little turbine cooldown.

01:19.905 --> 01:21.559
- Max!
- No, she's fine.

01:21.603 --> 01:24.171
She likes it.
God, it gets hotter every year.

01:24.214 --> 01:26.434
I can't believe
it's not even June.

01:26.477 --> 01:29.567
What is the world gonna be like
when you're a grown-up?

01:29.611 --> 01:32.266
Because it is a slow moving
train wreck right now,

01:32.309 --> 01:33.919
and nobody is doing anything--

01:33.963 --> 01:34.964
- Could you speak up?

01:35.007 --> 01:36.183
I can't hear you
over the turbines

01:36.226 --> 01:38.228
belching freon into the air.

01:38.272 --> 01:39.795
- Well, I make up for it,
all right?

01:39.838 --> 01:41.840
I turn on the low flow nozzle
in the shower.

01:41.884 --> 01:43.364
I compost.

01:43.407 --> 01:45.453
I turn off the faucet
whenever I'm brushing my teeth.

01:45.496 --> 01:46.976
Okay?
Every time.

01:47.019 --> 01:50.762
I have like 60 of those
reusable cloth shopping bags.

01:50.806 --> 01:52.721
- Yeah, so you won't mind
if I turn this off?

01:52.764 --> 01:54.592
- No, no, no,
just a second longer

01:54.636 --> 01:56.812
'cause it's, you know,
making her comfortable.

01:56.855 --> 01:59.249
- Yeah, which makes you
comfortable.

01:59.293 --> 02:01.643
Everyone talks a good game
about sacrifice

02:01.686 --> 02:04.036
right up until the second
it threatens their comfort,

02:04.080 --> 02:06.604
including you, Max.

02:06.648 --> 02:08.867
- ♪ Talk that talk, hey

02:08.911 --> 02:11.609
♪ Better walk that walk,
clap hands now ♪

02:11.653 --> 02:14.308
♪ Talk that talk, hey

02:14.351 --> 02:16.527
♪ Better walk that walk,
clap hands now ♪

02:16.571 --> 02:18.790
♪ Talk that talk, hey

02:18.834 --> 02:21.271
♪ Better walk that walk,
clap hands now ♪

02:21.315 --> 02:23.491
♪ Talk that talk, hey

02:23.534 --> 02:26.189
♪ Better walk that walk,
clap hands now ♪

02:26.233 --> 02:27.321
♪ Oh, yeah, it's so you

02:27.364 --> 02:28.670
- Coming through.

02:28.713 --> 02:29.975
- Jerry, tell me this isn't
how much trash

02:30.019 --> 02:31.412
you throw out every day.

02:31.455 --> 02:33.936
- Oh, no way.
- Thank God.

02:33.979 --> 02:37.026
- That's how much we throw out
by 7:00 a.m.

02:37.069 --> 02:40.377
- Hey, Jer, you dropped one.

02:40.421 --> 02:42.249
- Eh, toss it.
- Toss it?

02:42.292 --> 02:43.598
It's unopened.
- Don't worry about it.

02:43.641 --> 02:45.426
We got thousands
of these things.

02:45.469 --> 02:46.818
Most of the patients throw 'em
in the garbage anyway.

02:46.862 --> 02:48.168
You're cutting out
the middle man.

02:48.211 --> 02:49.908
- ♪ Talk that talk, hey

02:49.952 --> 02:52.998
♪ Better walk that walk,
clap hands now ♪

02:53.042 --> 02:55.479
♪ Talk that talk, hey

02:55.523 --> 02:57.612
♪ Better walk that walk,
clap hands now ♪

02:57.655 --> 03:00.223
- ♪ Talk the talk, baby

03:00.267 --> 03:02.660
♪ Walk the walk

03:02.704 --> 03:05.054
♪ Talk the talk, baby

03:05.097 --> 03:07.230
♪ Walk the walk

03:07.274 --> 03:10.059
[both panting]

03:10.102 --> 03:12.322
♪ Walk the walk

03:12.366 --> 03:15.107
♪ Talk the talk, baby

03:15.151 --> 03:17.284
♪ Walk the walk

03:21.244 --> 03:24.682
- I can't believe you took
a whole week off to be with me.

03:24.726 --> 03:28.599
- Well, I haven't taken
a vacation day since 2009.

03:31.080 --> 03:33.561
- So was it worth it?

03:33.604 --> 03:38.740
- I'm pretty sure I answered
that question several times.

03:40.307 --> 03:42.352
[phone chirps]
- Mm.

03:42.396 --> 03:43.701
You're gonna be late.

03:43.745 --> 03:47.357
- [sighs] I'm the boss.
Bosses can be late.

03:47.401 --> 03:50.360
- Well, in that case...

03:50.404 --> 03:52.057
- Not that late,

03:52.101 --> 03:55.409
but we can pick up right here
when I get back later.

03:57.280 --> 03:59.413
[groans]

04:02.981 --> 04:04.635
- Mina!

04:04.679 --> 04:07.377
Mina, the hospital
is the other way.

04:07.421 --> 04:08.987
Look, I know you're not
thrilled

04:09.031 --> 04:11.163
about the prospect of therapy,
but it helps to have someone

04:11.207 --> 04:13.949
to talk to who can see things
that you might be missing.

04:13.992 --> 04:16.560
- I'm not going to therapy.
- Mina, will you listen to me?

04:16.604 --> 04:17.996
- I mean, one of those
American therapists

04:18.040 --> 04:19.563
with those questions:

04:19.607 --> 04:21.261
How do you feel about this?
How does this make you feel?

04:21.304 --> 04:22.740
I'm not going back
to that hospital.

04:22.784 --> 04:25.308
- You need someone to talk to.
- [sighs]

04:25.352 --> 04:27.267
I agree.

04:30.008 --> 04:32.054
- Islamic Center?

04:32.097 --> 04:33.229
- Don't look so surprised.

04:33.273 --> 04:34.404
I grew up going to places
like this.

04:34.448 --> 04:36.276
- Yeah, no, of course.

04:36.319 --> 04:37.842
Mina, I'm not against
you coming here.

04:37.886 --> 04:40.323
It's just that I booked you
an appointment.

04:40.367 --> 04:42.804
- So you take it

04:42.847 --> 04:44.762
'cause I think you're the one
who's missing something,

04:44.806 --> 04:47.896
Ammeh Joon, and you don't
even know it's gone.

04:47.939 --> 04:50.899
[soft music]

04:50.942 --> 04:57.862
♪

04:59.168 --> 05:00.909
- Hey, Dr. Frome!

05:00.952 --> 05:02.432
- You need to take this.

05:02.476 --> 05:04.129
- Was that why you wanted
to see me?

05:04.173 --> 05:07.872
Man, I'm sorry.
I could have just come by.

05:07.916 --> 05:09.004
Yeah, I know.

05:09.047 --> 05:11.136
I should have told you
about Martin.

05:11.180 --> 05:13.487
- This needs to stop right now.

05:13.530 --> 05:15.097
- It was stupid.

05:15.140 --> 05:20.407
I--I didn't mean
to freak anybody out, I swear.

05:20.450 --> 05:21.886
It's only 'cause you wouldn't
see me.

05:21.930 --> 05:23.801
- You're not my patient
anymore.

05:23.845 --> 05:25.803
You're not
my husband's patient.

05:25.847 --> 05:28.676
Chance, you lied your way
into my home.

05:28.719 --> 05:32.027
- But you could help me

05:32.070 --> 05:34.638
when no one else could.

05:34.682 --> 05:36.684
I was getting better.

05:38.076 --> 05:40.818
You know it's true.

05:40.862 --> 05:42.342
I need you.

05:43.691 --> 05:45.388
- Just take the hat, please.

05:45.432 --> 05:47.042
- Don't do this to me.

05:47.085 --> 05:50.567
- I'm not doing anything
to you, Chance.

05:50.611 --> 05:53.048
These are the consequences
for your actions,

05:53.091 --> 05:56.051
your choices.

05:56.094 --> 05:57.879
And if you continue
down this path,

05:57.922 --> 05:59.794
I will get the police involved.

05:59.837 --> 06:01.186
- What?

06:01.230 --> 06:04.015
- For your safety and for mine,

06:04.059 --> 06:06.496
you can no longer see me
or my husband.

06:06.540 --> 06:08.455
Is that clear?

06:08.498 --> 06:12.110
This behavior is dangerous.
It is obsessive.

06:12.154 --> 06:14.199
And I don't want to do this,
but if you don't stop,

06:14.243 --> 06:17.072
I will be forced to file a
restraining order against you.

06:17.115 --> 06:19.379
[dramatic music]

06:19.422 --> 06:21.555
Now show me
that you understand.

06:21.598 --> 06:28.736
♪

06:39.007 --> 06:40.748
- There's the boss!

06:40.791 --> 06:42.489
Thought you decided you were
never gonna come back.

06:42.532 --> 06:43.968
How was the week off?

06:44.012 --> 06:46.536
- It was fantastic, could not
have been more relaxing.

06:46.580 --> 06:48.190
- I'm glad you're rested

06:48.233 --> 06:50.888
because your ED is a total,
complete train wreck right now.

06:50.932 --> 06:53.456
- Come on, we're always
in shambles during a heat wave.

06:53.500 --> 06:54.892
I'm sure it's nothing
we can't handle.

06:54.936 --> 06:56.720
- [chuckles]
You say that now.

06:56.764 --> 06:58.635
Before you let it rip,
I'm aware that we're not

06:58.679 --> 07:02.160
supposed to use the hallways
as overflow.

07:02.204 --> 07:05.903
- Casey, I appreciate you,

07:05.947 --> 07:07.427
and I don't tell you that
enough.

07:07.470 --> 07:09.559
- What?

07:09.603 --> 07:11.213
- Okay, where's Turan?

07:11.256 --> 07:13.433
- I know we're backed up.
I'm working as fast as I can.

07:13.476 --> 07:14.564
- It's fine.
You're fine.

07:14.608 --> 07:16.087
- It is?
I am?

07:16.131 --> 07:17.611
- Yeah, whatcha got?

07:17.654 --> 07:19.482
- Got a patient brought in
by a concerned family member

07:19.526 --> 07:21.484
complaining
of mild dehydration.

07:21.528 --> 07:23.443
[percussive music]

07:23.486 --> 07:25.140
- He doesn't look dehydrated.

07:25.183 --> 07:27.316
- That's because
he's not the patient.

07:27.359 --> 07:28.578
- Hey, Javier.

07:28.622 --> 07:30.624
Why don't you tell the doctor
what you can do?

07:30.667 --> 07:33.670
- I can control the weather
with my mind.

07:35.193 --> 07:38.588
- Okey dokey.
I am gonna be right back.

07:38.632 --> 07:40.895
Let's ask him
to make it cooler,

07:40.938 --> 07:42.897
and then get Iggy down here.

07:42.940 --> 07:44.942
- Dr. Bloom, I know you said
only bother you

07:44.986 --> 07:46.248
when absolutely necessary...
- [sighs]

07:46.291 --> 07:47.858
- Especially on a day
like today, but I--

07:47.902 --> 07:50.731
- Hit me, my friend.
- Oh, okay.

07:50.774 --> 07:52.384
We got an interesting case.

07:52.428 --> 07:53.777
Sister Edith Pursey,
a cloistered nun

07:53.821 --> 07:55.344
from the Monastery
of the Precious Blood.

07:55.387 --> 07:57.128
- Let me guess, she's hot.

07:57.172 --> 07:58.739
- No, she's cold--
freezing, actually.

07:58.782 --> 07:59.914
We just can't seem
to get her warm.

07:59.957 --> 08:02.220
Could be anemia.
She has a low hematocrit.

08:02.264 --> 08:04.309
- Okay, let's double up
the warming blankets,

08:04.353 --> 08:05.920
page Sharpe, and Dr. Walsh--

08:05.963 --> 08:07.791
- And here it comes.
- What?

08:07.835 --> 08:10.577
No, no, I was just gonna
suggest that you move her

08:10.620 --> 08:13.493
from the nurse's station
to a procedure room.

08:13.536 --> 08:16.234
Geez, why does everyone think
I'm gonna bite their head off?

08:16.278 --> 08:19.107
Who says you can't run an ED
and be nice to people?

08:19.150 --> 08:20.717
- You did.
You said that last week.

08:20.761 --> 08:22.806
- Dr. Bloom, we are officially
out of space,

08:22.850 --> 08:24.982
at capacity,
and it's not even lunch.

08:25.026 --> 08:27.202
- No problem, okay?
I am gonna fix it.

08:27.245 --> 08:29.509
It's easy-peasy, okay?

08:29.552 --> 08:32.642
Great work, everybody!
Great work.

08:32.686 --> 08:35.427
♪

08:35.471 --> 08:37.299
- Maybe I need a vacation.

08:39.214 --> 08:41.738
- The man knows Mama has
diabetes, Courtney.

08:41.782 --> 08:43.740
Every time I turn around,
boyfriend is showing up

08:43.784 --> 08:45.263
with poundcake
or scrapple and eggs.

08:45.307 --> 08:46.874
- What can I say?
They're in love.

08:46.917 --> 08:48.440
- Look, no one is taking this
seriously.

08:48.484 --> 08:51.139
I'm up three times a night
every week checking her levels

08:51.182 --> 08:53.228
'cause this guy's got
her blood sugar all jacked up.

08:53.271 --> 08:55.143
I'm telling you--
- Help, somebody help!

08:55.186 --> 08:57.014
He's trapped in the car!
- I gotta go.

08:57.058 --> 08:58.886
- Must be boiling in there.
- What's going on?

08:58.929 --> 09:00.844
- There's a kid in the car.
- Let me see.

09:02.367 --> 09:03.847
How long?
- Don't know.

09:03.891 --> 09:05.762
- I already called 911.

09:05.806 --> 09:08.025
- Anybody got a knife,
a pocket knife?

09:08.069 --> 09:11.115
Or a pen?
Like, a heavy-duty pen?

09:11.159 --> 09:12.377
- I have a pen.

09:12.421 --> 09:14.075
- All right, stand back.

09:15.337 --> 09:18.253
[car alarm ringing]

09:18.296 --> 09:21.256
[dramatic music]

09:21.299 --> 09:24.389
♪

09:24.433 --> 09:26.478
[grunts]
Okay.

09:26.522 --> 09:27.741
- Hey, man,
there's a hospital--

09:27.784 --> 09:29.046
- I know, I know.

09:29.090 --> 09:34.182
♪

09:34.225 --> 09:35.966
- Sorry, but we're at capacity.
- We're not staying.

09:36.010 --> 09:38.229
- What happened?
- Kid was locked in a damn car.

09:38.273 --> 09:40.710
He's got a core temp of 107.
Out of the way!

09:40.754 --> 09:42.407
I'm gonna get him up to the OR

09:42.451 --> 09:46.716
for sedation, intubation,
and cold water gastric lavage.

09:46.760 --> 09:48.849
- Your hand's bleeding.

09:48.892 --> 09:51.112
- Just a scratch.
[elevator dings]

09:51.155 --> 09:52.592
[sighs]

09:54.419 --> 09:56.247
- Oh, Max!

09:56.291 --> 09:58.249
About this heat wave--
- Yeah, tell me about it.

09:58.293 --> 10:00.861
Did you know that sea level
rise will nearly triple deaths

10:00.904 --> 10:02.036
from contaminated
drinking water

10:02.079 --> 10:03.254
by the end of the century?

10:03.298 --> 10:05.256
- Oh, and my ED is already
at capacity.

10:05.300 --> 10:06.780
This is not sustainable.

10:06.823 --> 10:08.738
- Couldn't agree more,
and we are part of the problem.

10:08.782 --> 10:09.870
Don't get me started

10:09.913 --> 10:11.349
on New Amsterdam's
carbon footprint.

10:11.393 --> 10:12.742
- I wasn't planning on it.

10:12.786 --> 10:15.876
So to my point, I need
more staff, overflow beds,

10:15.919 --> 10:17.878
and a second
ambulance triage unit.

10:17.921 --> 10:20.576
- I will do you one better.
- Overtime pay?

10:20.620 --> 10:24.493
- I'm gonna fix
global warming...

10:24.536 --> 10:28.279
at New Amsterdam.

10:28.323 --> 10:29.367
- [sighs]

10:31.979 --> 10:32.370
.

10:32.414 --> 10:34.851
- Melting polar ice caps,
deforestation,

10:34.895 --> 10:38.202
temperatures are expected
to rise at least ten degrees

10:38.246 --> 10:39.421
in the next century,

10:39.464 --> 10:41.553
and the people in charge
of solving this

10:41.597 --> 10:44.339
can't even agree
that it's real.

10:44.382 --> 10:46.080
So now it's up to us.

10:46.123 --> 10:48.430
- The radiology department?

10:48.473 --> 10:52.826
- Because global warming
is a healthcare emergency.

10:52.869 --> 10:54.088
[all ohh-ing]

10:54.131 --> 10:55.306
Who do you think's gonna
bear the brunt

10:55.350 --> 10:59.093
of unchecked wildfires,
mass migration,

10:59.136 --> 11:00.877
toxic algae blooms?

11:00.921 --> 11:03.488
- The radiology department?
- Hospitals.

11:03.532 --> 11:06.622
So here, today, together,
the people in this room

11:06.666 --> 11:08.972
are gonna take up the fight
against global warming.

11:09.016 --> 11:13.673
Now, I would like to debut
my new flagship program...

11:15.500 --> 11:17.459
"The Gloves Are Off."

11:17.502 --> 11:20.244
- Wait, literally?
- Yeah, literally.

11:20.288 --> 11:23.726
Single-use latex gloves account
for 20% of our medical waste.

11:23.770 --> 11:24.814
Do you know where that waste
ends up, Mike?

11:24.858 --> 11:26.598
- We need to wear gloves,
Dr. Goodwin.

11:26.642 --> 11:28.426
- Wrong answer.
On a barge, Mike.

11:28.470 --> 11:29.645
It ends up on a barge.

11:29.689 --> 11:31.908
I also would have accepted
"in our oceans."

11:31.952 --> 11:35.520
So we are all gonna try
something new.

11:35.564 --> 11:39.046
We are only gonna get one box
of gloves per day.

11:39.089 --> 11:40.917
- Per person?
- Wrong again.

11:40.961 --> 11:42.614
For the entire department.

11:42.658 --> 11:44.529
- What about
infectious patients?

11:44.573 --> 11:46.488
- Well, that's why
I chose radiology.

11:46.531 --> 11:48.098
Your patients
are already diagnosed.

11:48.142 --> 11:50.144
Nobody needs gloves to simply
walk a patient into an MRI.

11:50.187 --> 11:52.059
- But gloves are
how we protect ourselves

11:52.102 --> 11:54.061
from, you know, germs.
- Uh-huh.

11:54.104 --> 11:56.367
- But handwashing is undeniably
more effective,

11:56.411 --> 11:58.543
which is why every
scrubs station and bathroom

11:58.587 --> 12:01.285
on this floor has been stocked
with extra biodegradable soap.

12:01.329 --> 12:04.636
Now, who's ready to save
this planet?

12:04.680 --> 12:08.989
Say it with me, guys.
The gloves are...

12:09.032 --> 12:12.209
The gloves are...

12:12.253 --> 12:15.778
- Off.

12:15.822 --> 12:18.825
- Thank you, Jerry.

12:18.868 --> 12:20.348
- I'm not crazy.

12:20.391 --> 12:21.871
- No one said you were.

12:21.915 --> 12:23.177
I didn't say you were crazy.

12:23.220 --> 12:25.222
I just--you know,
it's rare to see someone

12:25.266 --> 12:27.137
who can control the weather
with their mind.

12:27.181 --> 12:29.357
- I knew it.
You don't believe me.

12:29.400 --> 12:30.575
- No, wait, wait.
No, no, no, no.

12:30.619 --> 12:32.012
- You know, it's my brother
who is sick.

12:32.055 --> 12:35.537
I just agreed to take him
to the emergency room.

12:35.580 --> 12:37.408
I don't need any of this.
- That's cool.

12:37.452 --> 12:39.846
We're just--
we're just talking here, okay?

12:39.889 --> 12:42.022
Just me and you.
Your brother, he's downstairs.

12:42.065 --> 12:44.894
He's getting his fluids
replenished, and...

12:46.940 --> 12:49.116
Can I come clean with you?

12:49.159 --> 12:50.595
Can we sit?

12:50.639 --> 12:52.467
Confession time here.

12:52.510 --> 12:54.034
The only reason
I brought you up here

12:54.077 --> 12:56.732
is because I'm kind of
a weather nerd myself.

12:56.776 --> 12:58.734
- You are?
- Just a touch.

12:58.778 --> 13:00.692
I named my first pet El Niño.

13:00.736 --> 13:03.739
- [chuckles]
- So yeah, you be the judge.

13:03.783 --> 13:05.741
I just--I have to ask you
a couple questions

13:05.785 --> 13:08.831
about your, you know,
your powers.

13:08.875 --> 13:12.052
This brutal heat wave outside,
is that...

13:12.095 --> 13:13.923
is that you?

13:13.967 --> 13:15.229
- Yeah.

13:15.272 --> 13:17.231
- Whoa.
[laughs]

13:17.274 --> 13:18.928
How do you--how do you do it?

13:20.800 --> 13:23.063
- I get this throbbing feeling.

13:23.106 --> 13:24.847
Starts in my head.

13:24.891 --> 13:27.284
Then it moves down
through my whole body.

13:27.328 --> 13:29.156
Then everything goes black,

13:29.199 --> 13:32.202
and that's when it got hot.

13:32.246 --> 13:35.075
- That's it?

13:35.118 --> 13:37.381
- Are we done here?

13:37.425 --> 13:39.688
- Wait, um, look.

13:39.731 --> 13:42.343
This is really exciting for me,
like, beyond,

13:42.386 --> 13:45.737
and I know it's a big ask,
but, um,

13:45.781 --> 13:49.002
Javier, can I get a scan
of that brain of yours?

13:49.045 --> 13:50.786
- A scan?
- Yeah, I just--

13:50.830 --> 13:53.615
I need to see what makes you
so special.

13:53.658 --> 13:55.878
I know that's a big ask,
like I said,

13:55.922 --> 13:58.272
and if you wanna say no, I will
respect that and back away,

13:58.315 --> 14:02.102
but I have to ask.

14:02.145 --> 14:03.930
- [chuckles]

14:03.973 --> 14:05.975
Sure.

14:06.019 --> 14:07.759
I guess.
- Yeah?

14:07.803 --> 14:10.023
- Yeah.
- Awesome.

14:10.066 --> 14:12.939
[laughs]
That's awesome.

14:12.982 --> 14:14.375
- I am so sorry

14:14.418 --> 14:16.681
to cancel Mina's session
last minute, Serena.

14:16.725 --> 14:18.683
No, no, everything's fine,

14:18.727 --> 14:20.337
except for the fact
that she doesn't listen,

14:20.381 --> 14:21.686
she's completely
out of control,

14:21.730 --> 14:25.212
and I don't know what more
I have to give her.

14:25.255 --> 14:27.344
Sorry?

14:27.388 --> 14:29.477
Me?

14:29.520 --> 14:32.132
No, I don't need therapy.

14:32.175 --> 14:34.003
I have to go, Serena.

14:39.487 --> 14:41.489
[sighs]

14:43.491 --> 14:45.710
Sister Pursey.
Hi, I'm Dr. Sharpe.

14:45.754 --> 14:47.408
I hear you're the only person
in the city

14:47.451 --> 14:49.062
not melting
from this heat wave.

14:49.105 --> 14:50.193
- [chuckles]

14:50.237 --> 14:52.804
It's not as promising
as it sounds.

14:52.848 --> 14:54.806
Don't tell me I got this virus.

14:54.850 --> 14:57.592
- Oh, no, no, it's not COVID.
- Okay.

14:57.635 --> 15:00.987
- Although your temperature
is still only 94.5.

15:01.030 --> 15:03.119
Do you mind if I take a look?
- No, please.

15:06.079 --> 15:08.995
- A little different from your
usual day-to-day, I imagine.

15:09.038 --> 15:13.521
- It's my first day outside
the convent in almost--

15:13.564 --> 15:15.479
oh, goodness--almost 30 years.

15:15.523 --> 15:18.743
- Gosh!
- Mm-hmm.

15:18.787 --> 15:21.529
- Well, I'm sorry this is where
you have to spend it.

15:21.572 --> 15:24.401
[soft dramatic music]

15:24.445 --> 15:26.577
Will you excuse me a moment,
please?

15:26.621 --> 15:28.449
- No, of course.
- Thank you.

15:30.581 --> 15:33.149
Dr. Walsh.

15:33.193 --> 15:36.587
I ordered four tests.
Why did I just see one?

15:36.631 --> 15:38.154
- Oh, I just ordered
the thyroid test.

15:38.198 --> 15:39.373
- And why would you do that?

15:39.416 --> 15:40.896
- Well, the ED was so jammed,

15:40.940 --> 15:43.029
and hypothyroidism seemed like
the obvious diagnosis.

15:43.072 --> 15:45.683
- So you thought
that you'd just ignore me

15:45.727 --> 15:47.120
and do whatever you wanted?

15:47.163 --> 15:49.774
Sorry, what year
of your residency are you in?

15:49.818 --> 15:51.907
- And let's all just
lower the temperature.

15:51.951 --> 15:54.127
A little heat joke
to diffuse the tension.

15:54.170 --> 15:57.695
- When I order four tests,
it's not a suggestion.

15:57.739 --> 16:00.829
It's an order.
- Helen.

16:00.872 --> 16:02.439
Walsh.

16:02.483 --> 16:04.354
[percussion music]

16:04.398 --> 16:07.357
We're doing the best we can.
What's going on with you?

16:07.401 --> 16:08.750
- With me?
[scoffs]

16:08.793 --> 16:10.970
What's going on with you?

16:11.013 --> 16:12.710
Actually, do you know what?
It's fine, it's fine!

16:12.754 --> 16:15.061
I'll run the tests myself.

16:15.104 --> 16:17.802
♪

16:17.846 --> 16:20.457
Fran, I need a full-body PET
scan on my incoming patient--

16:20.501 --> 16:22.242
not a half body,
not a quarter body,

16:22.285 --> 16:24.984
a full-body PET scan,
and you're out of gloves.

16:25.027 --> 16:26.681
- Yeah, we've already used up
our daily allotment

16:26.724 --> 16:28.117
of exam gloves.

16:28.161 --> 16:30.554
There's a ladies' room
with some biodegradable soap,

16:30.598 --> 16:34.297
or you can wipe your hands
on your pants.

16:34.341 --> 16:36.038
Max is solving global warming.

16:36.082 --> 16:38.432
♪

16:38.475 --> 16:40.173
- BP's down to 90 over 40.

16:40.216 --> 16:43.524
- Hang a bag of normal saline
at 15 degrees Celsius.

16:43.567 --> 16:45.308
Run it wide open
into his central line.

16:45.352 --> 16:47.876
- Repositioning the catheter.
Inflating manual cuff.

16:47.919 --> 16:48.964
- Core temps still elevated.

16:49.008 --> 16:50.618
- Then push .2 milligrams
of Ativan.

16:50.661 --> 16:51.923
- I need a syringe.

16:51.967 --> 16:53.621
- Drop the temp
on the cooling blanket.

16:53.664 --> 16:55.014
- Give me tape and scissors.

16:55.057 --> 16:57.233
- Come on, we've got to make
some headway here.

16:57.277 --> 17:00.323
Much longer
and his brain's gonna fry.

17:00.367 --> 17:01.977
- Get me four by fours.

17:02.021 --> 17:03.544
Gauze.

17:03.587 --> 17:05.807
- Core temp down to 38.2.

17:05.850 --> 17:07.983
- All right, lighten up
on the anesthesia.

17:08.027 --> 17:10.072
- Got it.

17:10.116 --> 17:11.682
- Oh, I didn't call
for a consult.

17:11.726 --> 17:14.511
- How's he doing?
- Alive, barely.

17:14.555 --> 17:16.731
Some idiot left him
locked in a car.

17:16.774 --> 17:19.516
In this weather,
that's borderline criminal.

17:19.560 --> 17:22.563
I'm sorry, why are you here?

17:22.606 --> 17:24.130
- He's my son.

17:24.173 --> 17:27.133
[dramatic music]

17:27.176 --> 17:28.525
♪

17:29.874 --> 17:31.789
- Gretchen, what's
with the gloves?

17:31.833 --> 17:33.661
Gloves, gloves.

17:33.704 --> 17:35.445
Are you kidding me?

17:35.489 --> 17:38.100
Who restocked the closet?
- I did.

17:38.144 --> 17:40.798
- I'm sorry, let me get
this knife out of my back.

17:40.842 --> 17:42.670
- Your heart's
in the right place, Max.

17:42.713 --> 17:43.845
- It is, so why--

17:43.888 --> 17:46.804
- But your idealism
is ridiculous.

17:46.848 --> 17:48.197
- You know
what's not ridiculous?

17:48.241 --> 17:51.026
Lung cancer, which is set
to increase exponentially

17:51.070 --> 17:53.768
from pollution unless
we do something, anything,

17:53.811 --> 17:56.162
about climate change,
like limiting exam gloves.

17:56.205 --> 17:57.902
- During a global pandemic,
Max?

17:57.946 --> 17:59.643
- CDC recommends soap and--
- Listen.

17:59.687 --> 18:01.297
If you want to battle
climate change,

18:01.341 --> 18:03.038
then become a vegetarian,

18:03.082 --> 18:05.345
buy an electric car,
invest in solar panels.

18:05.388 --> 18:07.347
There are any number of things
that you could do

18:07.390 --> 18:10.698
that we'd all be on board with,
but not like this.

18:10.741 --> 18:12.613
The gloves are back on.

18:16.878 --> 18:17.226
.

18:17.270 --> 18:19.098
- Max Begley Jr., come on!

18:19.141 --> 18:20.360
Joining the climate fight,
I'm so proud.

18:20.403 --> 18:21.622
- Well, it's now
or, quite literally, never.

18:21.665 --> 18:23.580
- Yeah, I'm in, I'm in.
110% in.

18:23.624 --> 18:25.452
When I think about the Earth
that our kids are inheriting,

18:25.495 --> 18:26.888
it just--it breaks my heart,
so I really hope

18:26.931 --> 18:28.933
this little glove debacle
doesn't slow you down any.

18:28.977 --> 18:32.154
- No, no way, I am committed
to ending global warming

18:32.198 --> 18:33.590
at New Amsterdam...
- Well, obviously.

18:33.634 --> 18:34.809
- Which by the way,
did you know,

18:34.852 --> 18:36.376
is causing massive upticks

18:36.419 --> 18:38.682
in vector diseases like
dengue fever, Zika, Lymes--

18:38.726 --> 18:41.032
- I'm already seeing increases
in stress, anxiety,

18:41.076 --> 18:42.164
sleep disorders
in neighborhoods

18:42.208 --> 18:43.252
with poor air quality, right?
- Yeah.

18:43.296 --> 18:44.906
- I mean, sacrifices
need to be made.

18:44.949 --> 18:47.213
- Which is why I just came up
with an even bigger idea.

18:47.256 --> 18:48.388
- Even bigger?

18:48.431 --> 18:50.346
Max Thunberg,
what have you done?

18:50.390 --> 18:52.957
- You eliminated red meat
from all patient meals?

18:53.001 --> 18:54.872
- Every rib, patty,
and sirloin.

18:54.916 --> 18:56.135
- But you can't do that.

18:56.178 --> 18:58.049
- I can, and I did

18:58.093 --> 18:59.529
because New Amsterdam
is getting ready

18:59.573 --> 19:01.401
for "turning down the meat
on global warming."

19:01.444 --> 19:04.099
- I'm not sure if that's
a slogan or an HR violation,

19:04.143 --> 19:05.361
but we are not complying.

19:05.405 --> 19:06.884
Do you hear me?
- [clears throat]

19:06.928 --> 19:11.715
New Amsterdam buys 7,384 pounds
of red meat per week.

19:11.759 --> 19:16.459
That is 13,291,000 gallons
of water,

19:16.503 --> 19:18.200
and do you want to guess
how much methane

19:18.244 --> 19:19.854
is produced by those cows?

19:19.897 --> 19:21.464
- No.

19:21.508 --> 19:22.813
- Good, 'cause that's the one
statistic I did not memorize,

19:22.857 --> 19:24.206
but it is a lot.

19:24.250 --> 19:25.338
- Dr. Goodwin, I don't think
you quite understand

19:25.381 --> 19:26.252
the effect this is going
to have--

19:26.295 --> 19:27.427
- No red meat?

19:27.470 --> 19:28.645
My patients are going
to revolt.

19:28.689 --> 19:30.212
There will be violence.
- Over this?

19:30.256 --> 19:31.735
Come on.
It's healthier.

19:31.779 --> 19:33.563
Studies show that cutting out
red meat reduces the risk

19:33.607 --> 19:35.348
of heart disease as well
as most cancers,

19:35.391 --> 19:36.958
and we've been doing it
in cardio for years.

19:37.001 --> 19:39.395
- Well, I don't work in cardio,
Dr. Goodwin, I work in OB,

19:39.439 --> 19:41.571
and when a patient's been
sucking ice chips for two days,

19:41.615 --> 19:43.399
squeezing a bowling ball
out of their vagina

19:43.443 --> 19:46.097
during an 18-hour labor,
believe me, they want blood.

19:46.141 --> 19:47.577
They want steak.
- Right, okay.

19:47.621 --> 19:49.753
Well, if new mothers are
craving iron post childbirth,

19:49.797 --> 19:51.842
you can lovingly
and instructively point them

19:51.886 --> 19:53.366
toward legumes.

19:53.409 --> 19:55.150
- You're gonna get me killed.
- Dr. Goodwin!

19:55.194 --> 19:57.935
Every single patient in post-op
is complaining about our food.

19:57.979 --> 19:59.459
- Yeah.

19:59.502 --> 20:02.157
How exactly is that any
different from any other day?

20:02.201 --> 20:05.247
[percussion music]

20:05.291 --> 20:06.988
- But without any history
of mental illness

20:07.031 --> 20:10.426
and his delusions,
it has to be one of two things:

20:10.470 --> 20:11.732
one, neurological--

20:11.775 --> 20:13.734
- My bet would be meningioma.
- Yeah.

20:13.777 --> 20:15.562
- A small tumor impeding
his limbic system

20:15.605 --> 20:17.128
could explain his behavior.

20:17.172 --> 20:19.261
- Right, or two,

20:19.305 --> 20:21.655
he's a Tempestarii.

20:21.698 --> 20:23.874
[soft music]

20:23.918 --> 20:25.659
- Just tell me.
- I'm glad you asked, Dr. Kao.

20:25.702 --> 20:27.617
Tempestarii were medieval
magicians who believed

20:27.661 --> 20:30.751
that they could control
the weather with their minds.

20:30.794 --> 20:32.622
[computer chirps]

20:32.666 --> 20:34.972
- That's odd.
- Well, not really.

20:35.016 --> 20:37.627
People used to believe
in giants back then, elves--

20:37.671 --> 20:39.107
- No, no, no.
- Wacky stuff.

20:39.150 --> 20:40.935
- I meant his scan.
- Oh, why?

20:40.978 --> 20:42.806
What do you see?
- Nothing.

20:42.850 --> 20:44.895
No meningioma, no tumors,

20:44.939 --> 20:47.507
nothing that would explain
his delusional state.

20:47.550 --> 20:50.640
- Well, what does that mean?
- It means you're right.

20:50.684 --> 20:53.513
He must be
a medieval weather magician.

20:55.341 --> 20:57.256
- [exhales]

20:57.299 --> 21:00.346
[monitor beeping]

21:07.527 --> 21:10.660
[soft dramatic music]

21:10.704 --> 21:14.273
♪

21:14.316 --> 21:16.536
- He's doing much better now.

21:19.234 --> 21:21.236
Thank you.

21:24.326 --> 21:26.285
I had six surgeries yesterday,

21:26.328 --> 21:28.591
one scheduled
for early this morning.

21:28.635 --> 21:30.811
The employee lot was full,
so I had to park on the street.

21:30.854 --> 21:32.943
- Hey, look,
I don't need to hear this.

21:32.987 --> 21:35.468
- I need you to understand.

21:35.511 --> 21:37.644
So I'm raising him on my own,

21:37.687 --> 21:39.776
and school's on, school's off.

21:39.820 --> 21:41.343
[sighs]

21:41.387 --> 21:43.258
Sometimes I drive him,
sometimes I don't,

21:43.302 --> 21:45.521
and so this morning,

21:45.565 --> 21:48.524
I drove to the hospital
instead of the school.

21:48.568 --> 21:51.962
I got an emergency page,
and so I just ran,

21:52.006 --> 21:54.878
and hey, I forgot.

21:58.360 --> 22:01.972
I--I forgot he was there.

22:02.016 --> 22:04.061
He was asleep.

22:04.105 --> 22:06.499
It was a mistake.

22:08.022 --> 22:10.329
- He's your son.

22:10.372 --> 22:11.895
He should have been
your priority.

22:11.939 --> 22:14.028
- He's m--he is.

22:16.291 --> 22:19.120
He is.

22:19.163 --> 22:21.122
- Tell that to social services.

22:21.165 --> 22:22.776
Maybe they'll understand.

22:26.649 --> 22:29.783
[monitor beeping rapidly]

22:29.826 --> 22:31.393
- What happened?
- She's in V-tach.

22:31.437 --> 22:34.309
Heart rate shot up to 150.

22:34.353 --> 22:37.007
- Clear.

22:37.051 --> 22:39.923
♪

22:39.967 --> 22:41.577
- She's back.

22:41.621 --> 22:43.449
- Okay, let's get her
on amiodarone,

22:43.492 --> 22:45.015
150 milligram IV.

22:45.059 --> 22:46.974
- That happened
because she has endocarditis.

22:47.017 --> 22:48.454
- What?

22:48.497 --> 22:49.933
- According to the test results
I ordered initially,

22:49.977 --> 22:51.805
she's fighting
a raging infection.

22:51.848 --> 22:54.547
- Walsh, let's get her
on triple antibiotic therapy,

22:54.590 --> 22:55.678
amp, gent, and vanco.

22:55.722 --> 22:57.288
- On it.

22:57.332 --> 22:58.812
- If your staff had just done
the work-up I asked them to

22:58.855 --> 23:00.770
in the first place, we would
have known this hours ago.

23:00.814 --> 23:02.555
Spared the woman a code--
- On your left.

23:02.598 --> 23:05.471
- You need an overflow, Lauren.
Your ED's a mess.

23:05.514 --> 23:07.777
- Yeah, well,
I spoke to Max this morning.

23:07.821 --> 23:09.300
He says he's on it.
- Ha!

23:09.344 --> 23:12.565
By taking away gloves from
radiology and meat from OB?

23:12.608 --> 23:14.175
- All right, I'll remind him.

23:14.218 --> 23:16.003
- Remind him?
Remind him?

23:16.046 --> 23:17.613
A week ago,
you would have demanded it,

23:17.657 --> 23:19.572
and he would've opened up
a triage unit already.

23:19.615 --> 23:21.965
Whatever the hell you did
on vacation,

23:22.009 --> 23:23.532
you need to shake it off.

23:23.576 --> 23:26.840
You've gone soft, and it's
putting our patients at risk.

23:26.883 --> 23:31.453
♪

23:31.497 --> 23:33.847
- Max, hey, hi.
So, listen.

23:33.890 --> 23:35.892
I just tried to order
a hamburger in the cafeteria--

23:35.936 --> 23:37.285
- I know, you can't.
Isn't that great?

23:37.328 --> 23:38.678
- Right.

23:38.721 --> 23:39.896
I was under the impression
this was more

23:39.940 --> 23:41.855
of a patient-centered
type program.

23:41.898 --> 23:43.291
- No, no, no.
It's gotta be hospital-wide.

23:43.334 --> 23:45.119
Otherwise patients would just
have family members

23:45.162 --> 23:47.469
go down to the cafeteria, and
they'd grab a burger for them,

23:47.513 --> 23:48.601
and then we'd be wasting

23:48.644 --> 23:50.341
all those perfectly good
vegetarian meals.

23:50.385 --> 23:51.821
- Right, yeah, uh-huh.

23:51.865 --> 23:54.345
But do we really want
to dictate what people can eat?

23:54.389 --> 23:55.651
Is that our thing?
- Yeah.

23:55.695 --> 23:57.261
I think that's exactly
what we want to dictate.

23:57.305 --> 23:58.959
- Well, what if a doctor just
wants a simple hamburger?

23:59.002 --> 24:00.221
- Then a doctor
can go off campus

24:00.264 --> 24:01.527
and get a simple hamburger.

24:01.570 --> 24:03.093
- What if a doctor has patients
all afternoon,

24:03.137 --> 24:04.486
and his 1:15 process meeting
got pushed back by half an--

24:04.530 --> 24:05.748
- Iggy, I thought
you were on board.

24:05.792 --> 24:09.056
- I am.
I am--oh, I so am.

24:09.099 --> 24:12.842
I just--you know,
I'm on the keto diet,

24:12.886 --> 24:14.844
and I'm not sure you know what
that does to a man, right?

24:14.888 --> 24:17.673
I'm giving up cake, and bread,
and desserts, and French fries,

24:17.717 --> 24:20.197
and every kind of sweet
you can imagine, you know?

24:20.241 --> 24:22.983
And I'm down to wrapping my
burger patty in wilted lettuce,

24:23.026 --> 24:26.377
and if we have it your way,
I'll just have, uh...

24:26.421 --> 24:28.249
I just have the lettuce.

24:28.292 --> 24:32.209
So you need to reinstate
the meat.

24:32.253 --> 24:34.298
- Okay.
- Okay?

24:34.342 --> 24:35.430
- Yeah.
- Really?

24:35.474 --> 24:36.823
- Sure, just answer me this:

24:36.866 --> 24:39.216
how are we gonna
make a difference

24:39.260 --> 24:42.655
when nobody is willing
to change a single thing?

24:42.698 --> 24:44.874
- No, no, no, no.
I am all for change.

24:44.918 --> 24:46.310
I'm all about change.
You know that.

24:46.354 --> 24:48.095
I'm here, I am down to change
the planet with you.

24:48.138 --> 24:49.270
I'm right by your side.

24:49.313 --> 24:52.534
Just, um...just not like this.

24:52.578 --> 24:54.710
♪

25:00.107 --> 25:00.324
.

25:00.368 --> 25:01.674
- How are we feeling, Sister?

25:01.717 --> 25:04.764
- B...

25:04.807 --> 25:06.461
B--

25:06.505 --> 25:07.854
B--mm.

25:07.897 --> 25:09.290
- Okay, just relax.
Relax.

25:09.333 --> 25:12.685
Dr. Bloom!
- Yeah?

25:12.728 --> 25:14.687
- It's okay.

25:14.730 --> 25:16.384
[tense music]

25:16.427 --> 25:18.081
- What's going on?
- She's slurring her words.

25:18.125 --> 25:20.780
She's aphasic.
- This isn't endocarditis.

25:20.823 --> 25:22.433
- How did I get it so wrong?

25:22.477 --> 25:24.218
Whatever it is,
it's moved up to her head.

25:24.261 --> 25:26.394
It's attacking her brain.
- Autoimmune disease.

25:26.437 --> 25:27.961
- But I would've seen signs
of inflammation.

25:28.004 --> 25:29.571
[light bulb shatters]

25:29.615 --> 25:32.226
- What the...?

25:32.269 --> 25:35.098
Excuse me.
What are you doing?

25:35.142 --> 25:37.057
- Swapping out all the
fluorescents in the hospital

25:37.100 --> 25:38.493
with energy-efficient LEDs.

25:38.537 --> 25:39.581
- Why?

25:39.625 --> 25:41.017
- Because Dr. Goodwin's

25:41.061 --> 25:42.845
"shedding light
on global warming."

25:42.889 --> 25:45.587
- And you're doing this now,
in the middle of the day,

25:45.631 --> 25:47.197
when we're stuffed
to the gills?

25:47.241 --> 25:49.983
- It's a big hospital.
Lot of light bulbs.

25:50.026 --> 25:53.203
And you're not supposed to be
wearing those gloves anymore.

25:53.247 --> 25:55.815
Kevin!
- That's it.

25:55.858 --> 25:58.905
Get me Max down here now.

25:58.948 --> 26:00.254
- Mom is having a problem.

26:00.297 --> 26:01.603
- What? What's up?
- You were right.

26:01.647 --> 26:03.649
Her blood sugar
is off the charts.

26:03.692 --> 26:05.041
- See?
[groans]

26:05.085 --> 26:06.913
This is exactly what I was
talking about.

26:06.956 --> 26:09.393
Okay, listen to me.
Go to the fridge.

26:09.437 --> 26:10.960
Give her ten more units
of insulin.

26:11.004 --> 26:13.136
It should be the last
of the bottle.

26:13.180 --> 26:14.529
- This bottle's full, Floyd.

26:14.573 --> 26:15.704
- It can't be.

26:15.748 --> 26:17.140
- Wait, there's another one
in here.

26:17.184 --> 26:18.315
- Another one?

26:18.359 --> 26:19.665
- It's an old prescription.

26:19.708 --> 26:21.144
- Wait, what?

26:21.188 --> 26:23.364
- It's expired.

26:23.407 --> 26:24.408
- No.

26:24.452 --> 26:26.628
No, no, no.
That's not right.

26:26.672 --> 26:28.369
- Yeah, it's in front
of the milk, right?

26:28.412 --> 26:30.937
Expiration five weeks ago.

26:30.980 --> 26:33.287
- Oh...

26:33.330 --> 26:35.115
That's what I've been
giving her all week.

26:35.158 --> 26:36.595
- Are you serious?

26:36.638 --> 26:38.074
The whole reason
you're staying with her

26:38.118 --> 26:40.555
is to monitor her meds--
you could have killed her!

26:40.599 --> 26:42.122
- It was a mistake, I--
[line hangs up]

26:42.165 --> 26:47.736
♪

26:47.780 --> 26:50.478
- Okay, so first of all,
let me thank you again

26:50.521 --> 26:52.132
for letting me take a look
at that brain of yours.

26:52.175 --> 26:54.438
What an honor.
- So you believe me?

26:54.482 --> 26:58.660
- You have quite the gift,
truly,

26:58.704 --> 27:00.706
and your brother and I
were actually hoping

27:00.749 --> 27:03.839
that maybe you would consider
staying on longer here

27:03.883 --> 27:07.669
at the hospital with me,
so I could study you further.

27:07.713 --> 27:10.454
- Um...

27:10.498 --> 27:11.760
no.

27:11.804 --> 27:13.022
- Just hear me out.

27:13.066 --> 27:15.503
Your power is unusual,

27:15.546 --> 27:18.985
and I would really like to know
what's actually happening here.

27:19.028 --> 27:20.943
I'm fascinated.

27:20.987 --> 27:23.816
♪

27:23.859 --> 27:25.731
- I knew it.

27:25.774 --> 27:28.211
I'm not making this up.

27:28.255 --> 27:31.127
We're trying to help you.
- By tricking me?

27:31.171 --> 27:32.520
Lying to me?

27:32.563 --> 27:34.914
Trying to lock me away
in some psych ward?

27:34.957 --> 27:36.045
- Because you're acting crazy!

27:36.089 --> 27:37.568
- Hey, now,
we don't use that term.

27:37.612 --> 27:39.658
- Javi, you're sick.
You need help.

27:39.701 --> 27:41.050
We're trying to help.

27:41.094 --> 27:42.791
- There's nothing wrong
with me.

27:42.835 --> 27:44.880
- Your brother is just
concerned for you, okay?

27:44.924 --> 27:48.057
He's worried.
We all just want what's best.

27:50.059 --> 27:52.018
- You want proof?

27:52.061 --> 27:54.020
Here's proof.

27:54.063 --> 27:56.239
♪

27:56.283 --> 28:00.722
[thunder booming]

28:00.766 --> 28:02.550
You want more proof?

28:02.593 --> 28:05.379
♪

28:05.422 --> 28:08.817
- Javier.
- How about this?

28:08.861 --> 28:10.732
[thunder continues booming]

28:10.776 --> 28:15.955
♪

28:15.998 --> 28:18.261
- Oh, oh, whoa, whoa, whoa.
Grab him, grab him.

28:18.305 --> 28:20.394
Gently, gently, gently.
Get him on his side.

28:20.437 --> 28:23.527
- Javi, open your eyes.
- Gladys!

28:23.571 --> 28:25.486
- Javi.

28:31.797 --> 28:33.233
- Yeah?

28:33.276 --> 28:35.017
- I asked you for help
this morning,

28:35.061 --> 28:36.715
and you have done
absolutely nothing.

28:36.758 --> 28:38.760
- I've been trying
to make changes all day.

28:38.804 --> 28:41.197
- To combat climate change.
- Exactly.

28:41.241 --> 28:43.156
- I asked you for help
in my ED, Max.

28:43.199 --> 28:45.375
- And my changes would
significantly reduce

28:45.419 --> 28:46.550
your patient load.

28:46.594 --> 28:49.205
- Years from now, not today.

28:49.249 --> 28:51.555
My ED is coding today.

28:51.599 --> 28:56.038
- Okay, so when do we make
changes?

28:56.082 --> 28:58.432
You tell me.
We run 24/7.

28:58.475 --> 28:59.781
There's never gonna
be a good time

28:59.825 --> 29:01.783
to change the lightbulbs,
or try a new policy,

29:01.827 --> 29:04.612
or do anything
of any consequence.

29:04.655 --> 29:07.876
We all say that we wanna fight
climate change,

29:07.920 --> 29:09.312
just not like this.

29:09.356 --> 29:10.792
Do you know what
"not like this" means?

29:10.836 --> 29:12.794
It means never,

29:12.838 --> 29:15.754
and never means
a lot of patients.

29:15.797 --> 29:17.494
It means human suffering
on a scale

29:17.538 --> 29:18.931
that we can't even imagine.

29:18.974 --> 29:20.541
- Max.

29:20.584 --> 29:22.891
- No, we can be a model for
other hospitals in New York,

29:22.935 --> 29:24.240
for the country, the world

29:24.284 --> 29:26.808
if we can cement
one single change--

29:26.852 --> 29:29.332
- Enough!

29:29.376 --> 29:32.205
I am running
an emergency department,

29:32.248 --> 29:34.511
not an environmental
think tank.

29:34.555 --> 29:36.644
I don't care about
my carbon footprint,

29:36.687 --> 29:38.602
or yours, or this hospital's.

29:38.646 --> 29:40.343
I don't care
how many gloves I use,

29:40.387 --> 29:43.259
or how many syringes I toss,
or my emissions.

29:43.303 --> 29:45.827
I care about the patients
in this ED

29:45.871 --> 29:48.438
lining these hallways
and waiting in ambulances

29:48.482 --> 29:50.484
halfway around the damn block.

29:50.527 --> 29:53.139
So stop making changes
that are gonna help people

29:53.182 --> 29:56.055
a hundred years in the future,
and get me more staff,

29:56.098 --> 29:58.231
more beds,
and a second triage unit,

29:58.274 --> 30:00.886
so we can start helping people
right now.

30:00.929 --> 30:07.457
♪

30:09.851 --> 30:10.069
.

30:10.112 --> 30:12.506
- Javier, the surgery was
a success.

30:12.549 --> 30:13.899
- How'd you know
how to fix him?

30:13.942 --> 30:15.683
- Do you guys know
what barometric pressure is?

30:15.726 --> 30:17.032
- I heard of it,

30:17.076 --> 30:18.904
but what's that got to do
with my brother's brain?

30:18.947 --> 30:20.427
- Excellent question.

30:20.470 --> 30:22.733
So barometric pressure
is the weight of the atmosphere

30:22.777 --> 30:24.561
all around us, and it can
affect the human body

30:24.605 --> 30:25.954
in many, many ways.

30:25.998 --> 30:28.783
Like, for example,
if the air pressure is lower,

30:28.827 --> 30:30.350
it pushes against
the body less,

30:30.393 --> 30:31.960
allowing tissues to expand.

30:32.004 --> 30:33.614
- And when the storm started,

30:33.657 --> 30:36.965
the drop in pressure opened
a fistula in Javier's brain.

30:37.009 --> 30:39.663
And that fistula was hiding
a small benign tumor,

30:39.707 --> 30:41.840
hiding it even from the MRI.

30:41.883 --> 30:44.712
And that's what was causing
Javier's delusions.

30:48.803 --> 30:51.893
- I know.
It's been that kind of day.

30:51.937 --> 30:53.982
- So I wasn't controlling
the weather?

30:54.026 --> 30:57.072
- No, no, the weather was
controlling you, in fact,

30:57.116 --> 30:58.900
which sadly is something
I think we're all gonna have

30:58.944 --> 31:01.163
to get used to.

31:05.864 --> 31:09.606
- How are you feeling, Sister?
- The same.

31:09.650 --> 31:11.870
What's wrong with me?

31:11.913 --> 31:13.393
- We have run some more tests,

31:13.436 --> 31:18.267
but at this stage,
we just don't know.

31:18.311 --> 31:19.834
- I have faith.

31:19.878 --> 31:20.922
- I'm not gonna lie.

31:20.966 --> 31:22.793
I could use some of that
right about now.

31:22.837 --> 31:25.448
Are there any spare rooms going
at your convent?

31:25.492 --> 31:28.538
- I'm not sure
that would be any help.

31:28.582 --> 31:31.280
I found mine on a bender
in Panama.

31:31.324 --> 31:33.326
- [chuckles]

31:35.632 --> 31:37.199
Oh, you're serious?

31:37.243 --> 31:39.636
You found your faith
on a bender in Central America?

31:39.680 --> 31:41.073
- Oh, yes.

31:41.116 --> 31:43.858
At your age, I was what you'd
call a raging alcoholic.

31:43.902 --> 31:46.339
- Sister Edith.
- It's true.

31:46.382 --> 31:51.039
That summer backpacking--
partying, really.

31:51.083 --> 31:55.087
I think it took about six weeks
until I lost everything,

31:55.130 --> 31:58.960
my backpack, my passport,
friends.

31:59.004 --> 32:04.748
I managed to push everyone
and everything away.

32:06.011 --> 32:08.883
I thought it would make me feel
more safe,

32:08.927 --> 32:12.931
but I was never so alone.

32:15.063 --> 32:18.371
And then suddenly, I wasn't.

32:18.414 --> 32:20.373
I had faith.

32:22.897 --> 32:25.465
It was all that was left,

32:25.508 --> 32:28.424
and what I was missing,

32:28.468 --> 32:30.818
and I never lost it again.

32:30.861 --> 32:34.387
[soft music]

32:34.430 --> 32:37.390
- In...in Panama.
- Yeah, that's right.

32:39.392 --> 32:42.308
- Will you excuse me a moment,
please?

32:42.351 --> 32:44.484
She has malaria.

32:44.527 --> 32:46.834
- What are you talking about?
She's a cloistered nun.

32:46.877 --> 32:50.055
- Yeah, now, but 30 years ago,
she was a party girl in Panama.

32:50.098 --> 32:51.491
- You can't be serious.

32:51.534 --> 32:53.449
- She had a whole life
before joining the convent.

32:53.493 --> 32:55.886
- So, what, it's been dormant
all this time?

32:55.930 --> 32:58.411
- And only now triggered
due to the heat wave.

32:58.454 --> 33:00.761
Look, her body temp,
her blood smear.

33:00.804 --> 33:02.981
- Cerebral malaria.

33:03.024 --> 33:06.071
Get her
on intravenous artesunate.

33:06.114 --> 33:07.420
- I just couldn't see it

33:07.463 --> 33:09.465
because I only saw one part
of who she is.

33:09.509 --> 33:11.598
- Apology accepted.

33:11.641 --> 33:14.818
[dramatic music]

33:27.657 --> 33:30.182
- Dr. Reynolds.

33:30.225 --> 33:31.705
- What's gonna happen to him?

33:31.748 --> 33:33.402
- There's a lot
to unpack there,

33:33.446 --> 33:35.926
but leaving a child locked
in a car in New York City

33:35.970 --> 33:37.450
can constitute endangerment.

33:37.493 --> 33:39.713
He could go to jail,
lose his son.

33:39.756 --> 33:41.889
- Is that...

33:41.932 --> 33:44.979
is that too far?

33:45.023 --> 33:46.633
- The boy was five,
Dr. Reynolds,

33:46.676 --> 33:48.069
abandoned in a car.

33:48.113 --> 33:49.636
You found him.
You saw.

33:49.679 --> 33:52.378
- Right, right, right, right,
but you didn't...

33:52.421 --> 33:54.119
you didn't see the look
on his face

33:54.162 --> 33:56.991
when he came into my OR,
he had the--

33:57.035 --> 33:58.427
his eyes.

33:58.471 --> 34:00.690
- I'm sure he felt awful,

34:00.734 --> 34:02.649
but our concern must be
for the safety of the child.

34:02.692 --> 34:04.999
- Right, right,
that's why I called, but...

34:05.043 --> 34:07.045
- But what?

34:07.088 --> 34:10.048
[soft music]

34:10.091 --> 34:12.485
♪

34:12.528 --> 34:15.009
- It was a mistake.

34:15.053 --> 34:18.404
He made a mistake.

34:18.447 --> 34:20.536
♪

34:20.580 --> 34:23.539
- Is this a recommendation
for leniency?

34:23.583 --> 34:26.586
- It's a recommendation
for forgiveness.

34:26.629 --> 34:33.506
♪

34:48.825 --> 34:51.567
- Coming through.
- Oop, sorry.

34:51.611 --> 34:54.962
Hey, Jerry, you need some help
with that?

34:55.005 --> 34:56.442
- I won't say no.

34:58.792 --> 35:00.272
I'm going to eight.

35:00.315 --> 35:03.231
- Yeah, or, and I'm really
gonna blow your mind

35:03.275 --> 35:05.190
with this one, we could get off
at the next floor

35:05.233 --> 35:06.756
and take the elevator?

35:06.800 --> 35:07.931
- No can do.
- No?

35:07.975 --> 35:09.803
- Gotta get in my steps.

35:09.846 --> 35:13.720
Heart issue, and I promised
my kids I'd stick around

35:13.763 --> 35:15.678
to see 'em get married,
have kids of their own.

35:15.722 --> 35:17.115
- Well, that must feel good.

35:17.158 --> 35:20.074
- Don't get me wrong, man.
The exercise sucks.

35:20.118 --> 35:22.990
[laughs]
I hate it, every step,

35:23.033 --> 35:26.211
but someone's gotta make sure
the grandkids are Mets fans,

35:26.254 --> 35:29.562
so I suck it up
and get it done.

35:29.605 --> 35:33.653
♪

35:33.696 --> 35:35.742
What's the smile for?

35:35.785 --> 35:37.222
♪

35:37.265 --> 35:39.180
- I owe you an apology.

35:39.224 --> 35:40.921
I came in here this morning
thinking

35:40.964 --> 35:42.923
that I could make changes

35:42.966 --> 35:45.708
without disrupting your lives.

35:45.752 --> 35:48.233
Clearly, I was wrong.

35:48.276 --> 35:52.541
So I'm gonna try
something else.

35:52.585 --> 35:57.111
I'm gonna disrupt your lives
on purpose.

35:57.155 --> 35:58.721
We're all
in favor of change

35:58.765 --> 36:01.246
right up until the moment
it makes us uncomfortable.

36:01.289 --> 36:03.422
So we're going
King Solomon here.

36:03.465 --> 36:05.337
Since I can't implement
any changes

36:05.380 --> 36:07.426
without upsetting someone,

36:07.469 --> 36:09.993
I'm gonna implement
all of my changes at once

36:10.037 --> 36:11.647
and upset everyone.

36:11.691 --> 36:14.172
- I didn't think
it could get any worse.

36:14.215 --> 36:16.435
- That's what they said
about climate change.

36:16.478 --> 36:18.524
I'm asking everyone
to be annoyed,

36:18.567 --> 36:21.440
inconvenienced, uncomfortable.

36:21.483 --> 36:24.269
It will unquestionably suck,

36:24.312 --> 36:27.272
but doing nothing is worse.

36:27.315 --> 36:29.012
So we'll all put up
with the lightbulbs

36:29.056 --> 36:30.405
and the fewer gloves.

36:30.449 --> 36:31.667
And the surgeons
will say goodbye

36:31.711 --> 36:32.929
to single-use scalpels,

36:32.973 --> 36:34.801
and the anesthesiologists
will account

36:34.844 --> 36:36.150
for their greenhouse gasses.

36:36.194 --> 36:39.197
We will all dig
a little deeper,

36:39.240 --> 36:41.416
and cope with a leafy salad

36:41.460 --> 36:43.462
because if we want any chance

36:43.505 --> 36:45.812
of a better future
for our kids,

36:45.855 --> 36:47.857
there is only one move left:

36:47.901 --> 36:52.035
suck it up and get it done.

36:52.079 --> 36:54.560
The only thing I can promise

36:54.603 --> 36:57.606
is that we'll all hate it
together.

36:57.650 --> 37:00.392
- Annoying, but inspired.

37:00.435 --> 37:03.308
- You know, I get that a lot.

37:03.351 --> 37:08.574
- So what ridiculous name
are we calling this program?

37:08.617 --> 37:10.880
- Our last chance.

37:10.924 --> 37:14.275
♪

37:14.319 --> 37:18.279
- Ah, Ignatius, you are needed.

37:18.323 --> 37:20.542
- Oh, somebody knows
my core issues.

37:20.586 --> 37:22.892
- Wine?
- Uh, yes, please.

37:22.936 --> 37:26.461
Thank you,
and do we have children?

37:26.505 --> 37:27.680
- We do.

37:27.723 --> 37:30.987
Saleem and Raffi
are mainlining "Fortnite,"

37:31.031 --> 37:33.599
Harper is on a clothing strike,

37:33.642 --> 37:36.602
Sameera will be back
from the park any minute,

37:36.645 --> 37:40.127
and I chose the hottest day
of the year to bake a chicken.

37:40.170 --> 37:42.390
- Oh, my gosh.
I love my life.

37:42.434 --> 37:45.132
I love you.
This is amazing, thank you.

37:45.175 --> 37:47.395
- Papa, Papa!

37:47.439 --> 37:50.137
I hit a ball!
- Ah, here's our slugger.

37:50.180 --> 37:52.531
- I hit an overhand ball.
- Yes, Sameera, that's--

37:52.574 --> 37:54.402
- Sweetheart, why don't you go
tell your brothers and sisters?

37:54.446 --> 37:56.317
- Oh, hold on, kiddo.

37:56.361 --> 37:59.668
Where did you get the hat?
- Your friend.

37:59.712 --> 38:02.584
[dramatic music]

38:02.628 --> 38:04.194
♪

38:04.238 --> 38:07.676
- "It hadn't rained for ages,
so the ground was very dry.

38:07.720 --> 38:10.331
"He stamped his hooves,
he reared, he bucked,

38:10.375 --> 38:14.814
and made the biggest
dust clouds ever."

38:14.857 --> 38:18.121
- ♪ Take my love

38:18.165 --> 38:21.386
♪ Take it slow

38:21.429 --> 38:25.128
♪ Night to night

38:25.172 --> 38:26.826
♪ It's finally home

38:26.869 --> 38:28.349
- "Just then, Mom called Gus.

38:28.393 --> 38:30.612
"'Come along, dear,
we're going on a long walk.'

38:30.656 --> 38:32.832
'But I wanna make dust clouds,'
said Gus."

38:32.875 --> 38:35.748
- ♪ Can you know

38:35.791 --> 38:38.577
♪ People are looking
for something ♪

38:38.620 --> 38:42.320
♪ They think they lost
long ago? ♪

38:42.363 --> 38:49.370
♪

38:57.117 --> 39:02.252
♪ When the hate blows over

39:02.296 --> 39:04.994
♪ Hold my hand out

39:05.038 --> 39:09.216
♪ I see your home

39:09.259 --> 39:16.266
♪

39:17.224 --> 39:19.313
- I hope you're hungry, boss.

39:19.357 --> 39:21.533
♪

39:21.576 --> 39:23.709
How was the first day back?

39:26.189 --> 39:28.540
- We have to break up.

39:32.718 --> 39:35.068
I--

39:35.111 --> 39:39.507
I run the ED
at a major hospital,

39:39.551 --> 39:42.467
and I don't have the time,
okay?

39:42.510 --> 39:45.165
To be thinking about the...

39:45.208 --> 39:48.037
smell of your hair
or your lips.

39:48.081 --> 39:49.778
You make me soft, okay?

39:49.822 --> 39:54.870
And soft puts my patients'
lives at risk.

39:54.914 --> 39:58.265
I'm sorry.

39:58.308 --> 40:00.702
But this is over.

